{"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0,"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[],"toc_visible":true},"kernelspec":{"name":"python3","display_name":"Python 3"},"language_info":{"name":"python"}},"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **Project Name**    - Uber Supply Demand Gap Analysis\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"vncDsAP0Gaoa"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"fIGDlhuTi7aY"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["##### **Project Type**    - EDA\n","##### **Contribution**    - Individual\n","##### **Name -** Sarthak Singh"],"metadata":{"id":"beRrZCGUAJYm"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **Project Summary -**"],"metadata":{"id":"FJNUwmbgGyua"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["\n","\n","This project is based on actual Uber ride request data collected over a five-day period. The dataset contains 6,745 ride requests and includes information such as Request ID, Pickup Point, Driver ID, Status, Request Timestamp, Drop Timestamp, Request Hour, Time Slot, and Ride Duration. The primary objective of this project was to identify and analyze the supply-demand gap in Uber's operations.\n","\n","The supply-demand gap refers to the difference between the total number of ride requests and the number of successfully completed trips. Ideally, every ride request should result in a completed trip. However, many requests remain unfulfilled because drivers cancel rides or no cars are available at the requested time.\n","\n","Out of 6,745 ride requests, only 2,831 trips were successfully completed, representing approximately 42% of total demand. The remaining 3,914 requests, accounting for nearly 58% of total demand, were not fulfilled. Among these, 2,650 requests were marked as \"No Cars Available\" and 1,264 requests were marked as \"Cancelled.\" This significant supply-demand imbalance negatively impacts both customer satisfaction and business performance.\n","\n","To perform this analysis, I used Excel, SQL, and Python. Excel was used for data cleaning, pivot table creation, KPI calculations, and dashboard development. SQL was used to perform detailed analysis of trip status, demand gaps by hour, pickup location analysis, driver cancellation behavior, and completion rates. Python libraries such as Pandas, Matplotlib, and Seaborn were used to conduct exploratory data analysis and create visualizations for deeper insights.\n","\n","The analysis revealed that the supply-demand gap is concentrated in specific time slots and pickup locations rather than being evenly distributed throughout the day. The worst-performing combination was **City pickup during the Early Morning time slot**, which recorded **1,205 unfulfilled requests**. Another major problem area was **Airport pickup during the Evening time slot**, which recorded **1,145 unfulfilled requests**. Airport pickups during the Night time slot also showed a significant gap with **421 unfulfilled requests**.\n","\n","Location-wise analysis showed that both Airport and City pickup points face challenges, but the nature of the problem differs. Airport locations experience a higher number of requests where no cars are available, indicating insufficient driver supply. On the other hand, City locations experience a larger number of ride cancellations, suggesting operational and driver-related issues.\n","\n","Further analysis of driver behavior identified drivers with unusually high cancellation counts, highlighting opportunities for performance monitoring and targeted intervention. Completion rate analysis also showed considerable variation between pickup locations, emphasizing the need for location-specific operational strategies.\n","\n","Based on these findings, several recommendations were proposed. These include increasing driver availability during high-demand early morning and evening periods, deploying a dedicated airport fleet, introducing incentive programs for drivers operating during peak demand hours, implementing stricter policies for repeated cancellations, and improving demand forecasting using historical ride request patterns.\n","\n","This project provided hands-on experience in data cleaning, dashboard creation, SQL-based business analysis, and Python-driven exploratory data analysis. More importantly, it demonstrated how data-driven decision-making can be used to identify operational bottlenecks and improve business performance in real-world ride-sharing platforms such as Uber.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"F6v_1wHtG2nS"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **GitHub Link -**"],"metadata":{"id":"w6K7xa23Elo4"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["https://github.com/sarthaksingh3007-crypto"],"metadata":{"id":"h1o69JH3Eqqn"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **Problem Statement**\n"],"metadata":{"id":"yQaldy8SH6Dl"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**How can Uber identify the key time slots and pickup locations where the supply-demand gap is highest and what strategies can be implemented to reduce unfulfilled ride requests?**"],"metadata":{"id":"DpeJGUA3kjGy"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["#### **Define Your Business Objective?**"],"metadata":{"id":"PH-0ReGfmX4f"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["To analyze Uber ride request data and identify when and where the supply-demand gap is highest, so that Uber can take targeted actions to reduce cancelled and unfulfilled trips,improve driver availability and increase overall trip completion rate."],"metadata":{"id":"PhDvGCAqmjP1"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **General Guidelines** : -  "],"metadata":{"id":"mDgbUHAGgjLW"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["1.   Well-structured, formatted, and commented code is required.\n","2.   Exception Handling, Production Grade Code & Deployment Ready Code will be a plus. Those students will be awarded some additional credits.\n","     \n","     The additional credits will have advantages over other students during Star Student selection.\n","       \n","             [ Note: - Deployment Ready Code is defined as, the whole